"Frenz M., Henrich R.","Carbonate dissolution revealed by silt grain-size distribution: Comparison of Holocene and Last Glacial Maximum sediments from the pelagic South Atlantic",2007,"Sedimentology","54","2",,"391","404",,,10.1111/j.1365-3091.2006.00841.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33947238326&partnerID=40&md5=71caed4a3366745b251e4f19e6e579c6","Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, P.O. Box 330440, D-28334 Bremen, Germany; National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Waterfront Campus, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","Frenz, M., Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, P.O. Box 330440, D-28334 Bremen, Germany, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Waterfront Campus, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Henrich, R., Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, P.O. Box 330440, D-28334 Bremen, Germany","The current issue of global warming and the role of the ocean in global exchange of CO2 increases the interest in solid budgets of marine carbonate production and dissolution. The present study utilizes grain-size composition of pelagic sediments in order to trace spatial and temporal variability of carbonate sedimentation in the South Atlantic for the Holocene and Last Glacial Maximum (LGM, 19-23 cal kyr BP). A decrease in grain size (e.g. sand content, mean grain size of coarse carbonate silt) indicates increased carbonate dissolution as a result of increased fragmentation of calcareous microfossils. The spatial grain-size pattern suggests a threshold water depth below which a gradual grain-size decrease becomes increasingly rapid. This water depth is considered as the sedimentary lysocline. For the Holocene time slice, a constant, gradual decrease of foraminifer carbonate of about 5-10% per 1000 m water depth above the lysocline gives evidence for supra-lysoclinal dissolution. The water depth of the lysocline for the Holocene is tied to the interface of North Atlantic Deep Water and Antarctic Bottom Water (AABW) (ca 4100 m). Submarine ridges which restrict intrusion of AABW into the Angola Basin cause an asymmetry in carbonate preservation across the Mid-Atlantic Ridge. The lysocline was reconstructed at ca 3100 m for the LGM. These data suggest that the ca 1000 m rise of the lysocline eradicated the Holocene east-west asymmetry. © 2007 The Authors. Journal compilation 2007 International Association of Sedimentologists.","Carbonate dissolution; Carbonate sedimentation; Grain size; Holocene; Last Glacial Maximum; South Atlantic","carbonate sediment; dissolution; global warming; grain size; Holocene; Last Glacial Maximum; lysocline; marine sediment; Angola Basin; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (South); Foraminifera",,,,,,"Antoine, D., André, J.-M., Morel, A., Oceanic primary production-2. Estimation at global scale from satellite (coastal zone colour scanner) chlorophyll (1996) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 10, pp. 57-69; Archer, D.E., Emerson, S., Maier-Reimer, E., Dissolution of calcite in deep-sea sediments: pH and O2 microelectrode results (1994) Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 53, pp. 2831-2845; Baumann, K.-H., Cepek, M., Kinkel, H., Coccolithophores as indicators of ocean water masses, surface-water temperature, and paleoproductivity - Examples from the South Atlantic (1999) Use of Proxies in Paleoceanography - Examples from the South Atlantic, pp. 117-144. , In: (Eds G. Fischer and G. Wefer), Springer-Verlag, Berlin; Baumann, K.-H., Boeckel, B., Donner, B., Gerhardt, S., Henrich, R., Vink, A., Volbers, A., Zonneveld, K.A.F., Contribution of calcareous plankton groups to the carbonate budget of South Atlantic surface sediments (2004) The South Atlantic in the Late Quaternary; Reconstruction of Material Budget and Current Systems, pp. 81-99. , In: (Eds G. Wefer, S. Mulitza and V. Ratmeyer), Springer-Verlag, Berlin; Berger, W.H., Planktonic foraminifera: Selective solution and paleoclimatic interpretation (1968) Deep-Sea Res., 15, pp. 31-43; Berger, W.H., Preservation of foraminifera 